        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/listen": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/listen",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "Serves a wiki over HTTP.\n\nThe listen command uses NamedCommandParameters:\n\n```\n--listen [<name>=<value>]...\n```\n\nAll parameters are optional with safe defaults, and can be specified in any order. The recognised parameters are:\n\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''credentials'' - pathname of credentials CSV file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''anon-username'' - the username for signing edits for anonymous users\n* ''username'' - optional username for basic authentication\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''authenticated-user-header'' - optional name of header to be used for trusted authentication\n* ''readers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to read from this wiki\n* ''writers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to write to this wiki\n* ''csrf-disable'' - set to \"yes\" to disable CSRF checks (defaults to \"no\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''tls-cert'' - pathname of TLS certificate file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''tls-key'' - pathname of TLS key file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nFor information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"

            "text": "(Note: The `--savetiddlers` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--save` command)\n\nSaves a group of tiddlers in their raw text or binary format to the specified directory.\n\n```\n--savetiddlers <filter> <pathname> [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nThe output directory is cleared of existing files before saving the specified files. The deletion can be disabled by specifying the ''noclean'' flag.\n\nAny missing directories in the pathname are automatically created.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki (deprecated in favour of the new listen command)",
            "text": "Legacy command to serve a wiki over HTTP.\n\n```\n--server <port> <root-tiddler> <root-render-type> <root-serve-type> <username> <password> <host> <path-prefix> <debug-level>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation should only be used on a trusted network or over HTTPS.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password.\n\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nUsing an address like this exposes your system to the local network. For information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },

For example:\n\n```\n\t$$latex-goes-here$$\n```\n\nThis wikiparser can be modified using the rules eg:\n\n```\n\\rules except latex-parser \n\\rules only latex-parser \n```\n\n\\*/\n(function(){\n\n/*jslint node: true, browser: true */\n/*global $tw: false */\n\"use strict\";\n\nexports.name = \"latex-parser\";\nexports.types = {inline: true};\n\nexports.init = function(parser) {\n\tthis.parser = parser;\n\t// Regexp to match\n\tthis.matchRegExp = /\\$\\$(?!\\$)/mg;\n};\n\nexports.parse = function() {\n\t// Move past the match\n\tthis.parser.pos = this.matchRegExp.lastIndex;\n\tvar reEnd = /\\$\\$/mg;\n\t// Look for the end marker\n\treEnd.lastIndex = this.parser.pos;\n\tvar match = reEnd.exec(this.parser.source),\n\t\ttext,\n\t\tdisplayMode;\n\t// Process the text\n\tif(match) {\n\t\ttext = this.parser.source.substring(this.parser.pos,match.index);\n\t\tdisplayMode = text.indexOf('\\n') != -1;\n\t\tthis.parser.pos = match.index + match[0].length;\n\t} else {\n\t\ttext = this.parser.source.substr(this.parser.pos);\n\t\tdisplayMode = false;\n\t\tthis.parser.pos = this.parser.sourceLength;\n\t}\n\treturn [{\n\t\ttype: \"latex\",\n\t\tattributes: {\n\t\t\ttext: {\n\t\t\t\ttype: \"text\",\n\t\t\t\tvalue: text\n\t\t\t},\n\t\t\tdisplayMode: {\n\t\t\t\ttype: \"text\",\n\t\t\t\tvalue: displayMode ? \"true\" : \"false\"\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}];\n};\n\n})();\n",

            "module-type": "wikirule"

Reference:\n\n# Mathematical typesetting: [ext[https://katex.org/docs/supported.html]]\n# Chemical typesetting: [ext[https://mhchem.github.io/MathJax-mhchem/]]\n\n<hr>\n\nThe usual way to include ~LaTeX is to use `$$`. For example:\n\n```\n$$\\displaystyle f(x) = \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty\\hat f(\\xi)\\,e^{2 \\pi i \\xi x}\\,d\\xi$$\n```\n\nSingle line equations will render in inline mode. If there are newlines between the `$$` delimiters, the equations will be rendered in display mode.\n\nThe underlying widget can also be used directly, giving more flexibility:\n\n```\n<$latex text=\"f(x) = \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty\\hat f(\\xi)\\,e^{2 \\pi i \\xi x}\\,d\\xi\" displayMode=\"true\"></$latex>\n```\n\nThe KaTeX widget is provided under the name `<$latex>` and is also available under the alias `<$katex>`. It's better to use the generic `<$latex>` name unless you are running multiple ~LaTeX plugins and wish to specifically target KaTeX.\n"

!!Meetings

''Frequent topics''

*the location and how the conference has been organized
* the social events (including tourist excursions) connected with the conference
* the weather
* the food
* other people's presentations
* latest technology (cellphone, PCs, etc.)
* the less specific ones: family, work, education, sport, film, music, and the political and economic situation of one or more countries.

''Safer topics about cultures''

*legal age to do certain things
*dialects and different languages within the same national borders
*the role of the family (e.g., treatment of the elderly, the age people leaves home)
*things people do for fun
*tipping habits
*holiday destination
*jobs; how often people change them; how far to commute
*national sports
*natural resources
*shop and office opening and closing time
*punctuality and its importance

''Prepare anecdotes that you can use to initiate topic with''

*travel stories
*misadventures in the lab
*the worst presentation you ever did
*the best/worst conference you ever attended
* factoid about your country/research area

''Be more active than a mere listener, learn to interrupt''

''Anticipate questions about your presentation''

''Meeting a key person''

*contact in advance
* try to think how you can be beneficial to him
* encourage him to come to your session

----

!!Introducing Yourself

*name, position, research
*`hi, do you have some minutes for questions?`
*Be prepared for what to say if your proposal for a meeting is rejected.

----
!!Good communication

*don't only ask questions, but also have announcements.
*offer more information than asked for
*avoid dominating the conversation
*feel free to interrupt who talks too much
*involve everyone in the conversation
*avoid long silence: return to previous topics, or start a new one
*avoid sounding rude
*express disagreement diplomatically
*dealing with difficult questions: 
**`I really don't have opinions on that.`
**`That may be. I couldn't really say.`
**`Why, what do you think about it?`
**`I'm sorry, I don't want to go into that.`
*Have ready excuse for ending an conversation







[ext[Useful Phrases 1|./materials/books/Adrian_Wallwork_Useful_Phrases.pdf]]

Phrases for emails, dealing with reviews/editors, telephoning, socializing, etc.

----

[ext[Useful Phrases 2|./materials/books/Adrian_Wallwork_Useful_Phrases.pdf]]

Phrases for presentation and networking.






''Informal comments''

*give explicit instructions on how you want the work to be reviewed
*construct:
**begin with a friendly comment
**show interests
**identify the good parts, say something positive
**tell the authors what you have done
**be constructive and avoid negativity
**offer further helps if available: further discussion on the suggested things for example
*be diplomatic when sending reminders: `Sorry to bother you again, but I urgently need you to answer these questions`
*be appreciative for the review

''giving review''

*be positive
*on whose behalf do you assess it?
*expectation:competent, consistent, constructive, highly knowledgeable, neutral, scrupulous, sympathetic
*soft approach when criticizing
*variations on should:
**please could you do A.
**I would recommend that
**It would be advisable to
**It might help the reader if the author does A.
*Use separate paragraphs to outline the comments.
*make sure the advices are explicitly doable.
*"you" for author, "I" for reviewer.
*bad english: differentiating grammer and typos.

''Replying to Reviews'':

*be proactive: write a discuss session, address other versions of the interpretation.
*please the referees: point out where they're right
*clear layout: paste replies under each comments; put comments in italics
*be brief
*call yourself "we"
*point out where you don't understand: `unfortunately we were not able to understand this comment`
*use the present and present perfect tense to outline the changes that has been made.
*justify why and where the changes are not made
*be diplomatic when having disagreements.

''Communicating with editors''

*convince them the importance of your work in a way as shortly as possible
*be diplomatic






''Subject Line: ''

*imagine in the prospective of the recipient.
*combine with the preview pane
*can give complete message
*two part subject line: `context: content`
*be specific
*include pertinent details for the recipient

''Beginning and Ending''

*spell the recipient's name correctly: cut and paste from the signature.
*be specific and straight at the start.
*"best regard" is the safe option, and "sincerely yours" is the formal one.
*`dear professor yuan`. Don't use `hi`, don't use `prof.`.
*provide a reminder of the background, if there is previous contact
*signature should contain all useful information: name, position, department, phone number
*avoid using PS

''Structuring the Content of an Email''

*immediately the point
*concise and precise
*use short sentences. choose the best grammatical subject.
*long mails will be scrolled: so use bullet, bold, and white spaces.
*use link words in long sentences.
*avoid ambiguity: fewer "him/her", 
*time zones should be taken care of
*if the mail is very important, have it checked by an expert

''Making Request''

*one important request, or several not so ones?
*give all the information they need
*consider not sending attachment to one without previous contact. just mention that you can send it if necessary.
*include relevant information that helps with decision
*lay out request clearly.
*short
*if too many and too long, include a mini-summary in the end.
*insert friendly comments
*give deadlines
*motivating the recipient to reply by emphasizing their situation and by paying them a compliment

''Deciding the level of formality''

*"how are you?" etc.
*maintain friendliness
*non-aggressive approach
*be careful when making request
*don't mix the level of formality
*add a friendly phrase at the end of mail

{{Algorithms}}






<<list-links filter:"[tag[Algorithm]]">>






[[Official website|http://www2.pv.infn.it/~hepcomplex/babayaga.html]]

*[[Babayaga Generator Paper 1]]
*[[Babayaga Generator Paper 2]]
*[[Babayaga Generator Paper 3]]








!!Matching perturbative and Parton Shower corrections to Bhabha process at flavour factories

[[arxiv|https://arxiv.org/abs/hep-ph/0607181]]

We report on a high-precision calculation of the Bhabha process in Quantum Electrodynamics, of interest for precise luminosity determination of electron-positron colliders involved in R measurements in the region of hadronic resonances. The calculation is based on the matching of exact next-to-leading order corrections with a Parton Shower algorithm. The accuracy of the approach is demonstrated in comparison with existing independent calculations and through a detailed analysis of the main components of theoretical uncertainty, including two-loop corrections, hadronic vacuum polarization and light pair contributions. The calculation is implemented in an improved version of the event generator BABAYAGA with a theoretical accuracy of the order of 0.1%. The generator is now available for high-precision simulations of the Bhabha process at flavour factories.






!!Photon pair production at flavour factories with per mille accuracy

[[arxiv|https://arxiv.org/abs/0801.3360]]

We present a high-precision QED calculation, with 0.1% theoretical accuracy, of two photon production in e+e− annihilation, as required by more and more accurate luminosity monitoring at flavour factories. The accuracy of the approach, which is based on the matching of exact next-to-leading order corrections with a QED Parton Shower algorithm, is demonstrated through a detailed analysis of the impact of the various sources of radiative corrections to the experimentally relevant observables. The calculation is implemented in the latest version of the event generator BabaYaga, available for precision simulations of photon pair production at e+e− colliders of moderately high energies.






!!The BABAYAGA event generator

[[arxiv|https://arxiv.org/abs/hep-ph/0312014]]

The program BABAYAGA is an event generator for QED processes at flavour factories, mainly intended for luminosity measurement of e+ e- colliders in the center of mass range 1-10 ~GeV. Recently, the pi+ pi- channel has been added as well. The relevant (photonic) radiative corrections are simulated by means of a Parton Shower in QED. The theoretical precision of the approach is estimated and some phenomenological results are discussed.

''Write python scripts instead'': it's easier to write a script with the os module in python.

[[Running Shell Commands with Python]]

----
!The Basics
A bash script start with the header `#!/bin/bash `, then it can be as simple as a collection of [[linux command lines|Linux Shell Commands]]. But there're more to it.

!!Comment Out A Line
*`# your comments`

!!Variables:
*Definition or set value: `var_name=value`
*Assess value: `$var_name`

!!Use the Output of Commands
*`$(command)`

!!Arithmetic evaluation:
*`echo 1 + 1`: string
*`echo $((1+1))`, `echo $[1+1]`: value, @@color:green;but only integers.@@

!!Parameters
*`$1`,`$2` and so on. `$*` for the list, `$#` for the number.


----
!More:
*[[Operators|Bash_Operators]]
*[[Conditions|Bash_Conditions]]
*[[Loop|Bash_Loop]]
*[[Functions|Bash_Functions]]

!Useful Codes
*[[Delete Condor Jobs|bash: delete condor jobs]]

*[[Salvage partially corrupted data|bash: salvage partially corrupted data]]






!!Deleting Condor Jobs in an ID Range.

```
#!/bin/bash
# This script remove the jobs whose id range from [$1,$2] or [$1,inf];
# if $#==0, do nothing, to avoid mistakenly deleting all jobs

nline=`hep_q -u yangyf| wc -l`
nline=$(( nline - 2 ))

if [ $# -lt 2 ]; then
        max_id=99999999
else
        max_id=$2
fi
if [ $# -lt 1 ]; then
        echo Need starting/ending JobID as parameters
        exit
else
        min_id=$1
fi

echo "minID: $min_id maxID: $max_id"

hep_q -u yangyf > info.txt

for i in `seq 3 $nline`; do
        jobid=`cat info.txt| head -$i |tail -1| cut -d "." -f 1 `
        if [[ ("$jobid" -le "$max_id")  &&  ("$jobid" -ge "$min_id") ]]
        then
                hep_rm $jobid
        fi
done
```






Detect failed jobs from logfile, and re-submit the jobs.

```
for x in `cat logfiles/dig4210 | sed '/success/d' | awk -F'.' '{print $1}'`; do boss.condor $x.txt; done
```






If part of the MC data failed to be generated, one may randomly reuse some other data to get the total number right.

1. Get the number of bad files N

```
du MC_* | grep ^4 | wc -l   
```

2. Remove these bad files

```
rm `du MC_* | grep ^4 | awk '{print$2}'` 
```

or remove bad dst according to logfile

```
for x in `cat ../logfile | sed '/Finalize/d' | awk -F'.' '{print $1}' | awk -F'_' '{print $2}'`; do rm *$x*; done
```

3. Duplicate the first N good root files, and `hadd`

```
for x in `ls MC_* | head -N`; do cp $x s$x; done
hadd result.root MC_*.root sMC_*.root
```

or duplicate the dst files:

```
for x in `seq -w 200`; do
if [[ `ls *$x* | wc -l` == 0 ]]; then
	idx=`echo $x |sed 's/^00//' | sed 's/^0//'`

	idx2=$(($idx -1))
	if [[ ${#idx2} -le 1 ]]; then
		idx2=`echo 0$idx2`
	fi
	if [[ ${#idx2} -le 2 ]]; then
		idx2=`echo 0$idx2`
	fi
	echo $idx2, $x
	cp MC_$idx2.dst MC_$x.dst
fi
done

```







!!Save and Load Paths
Save the paths to a file, so the tags can cross tab.

in `~/.bashrc`

```
for idx in `seq 1 9`; do  
        alias sd$idx="pwd > ~/scripts/.saved_dir$idx"
        alias cd$idx="cd `cat ~/scripts/.saved_dir$idx`  " 
        alias pd$idx="cat ~/scripts/.saved_dir$idx"
done

alias pd='echo "Print Saved Paths:"; for i in `seq 1 9`; do  echo $i: `cat ~/scripts/.saved_dir$i`; done'
alias cleard='for i in `seq 1 9`; do  echo "/" > ~/scripts/.saved_dir$i ; done'

```

@@color:blue; A bug is introduced in the new version, maybe should discard the usage of `$` and use `'` instead of `"`.@@






!!Conditions
*If-then:

```
if [ "foo" = "foo" ]; then
   echo expression evaluated as true
fi
```

*If-then-else with variables:
* and(&&)/or(||)


```
T1="foo"
T2="bar"
T3="t3"
if [[ ("$T1" = "$T2") && ("$T1" = "$T3") ]]; then
    echo expression evaluated as true
else
    echo expression evaluated as false
fi
```

*Case:

```
case $rental in
   "car") echo "For $rental Rs.20 per k/m";;
   "van") echo "For $rental Rs.10 per k/m";;
   "jeep") echo "For $rental Rs.5 per k/m";;
   "bicycle") echo "For $rental 20 paisa per k/m";;
   *) echo "Sorry, I can not gat a $rental for you";;
esac
```






!Functions:

```
function func_name{
        local local_var=value
        echo $HELLO
 }
```

Run a function: `func_name`

With parameters

```
function f1 {
    echo $1 
}
f1 par1
```







!!Loops
For:

```
for i in $( ls ); do
    echo item: $i
done
```

```
for i in `seq 1 10`; do
        echo $i
done
```

While:

```
COUNTER=0
while [  $COUNTER -lt 10 ]; do
    echo The counter is $COUNTER
    let COUNTER=COUNTER+1 
done
```

Until:

```
COUNTER=20
until [  $COUNTER -lt 10 ]; do
    echo COUNTER $COUNTER
    let COUNTER-=1
done
```






!!Operators
Operators are used in the statements of Bash scripts, utilized mainly in flow control.

!!String Comparison Operators
#`str1 = str2`: @@color:green;use `x$1=x$2` to avoid parse error when having empty strings@@
#`str1 != str2`
#`str1 < str2`
#`str1 > str2`

!!Arithmetic Operators
`+`,`-`,`*`,`/`,`%`

!!Arithmetic Relational Operators
#`-lt`:<
#`-gt`:>
#`-le`: <=
#`-ge`:>=
#`-eq `:==
#`-ne` :!=







''Minimalist Latex Document''

```
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}
Hello world!
\end{document}
```

''Some symbols''

`        `: consecutive spaces = 1 space.

`//`: force breaking line.

`# $ % ^ & _ { } ~ ` <===   `\# \$ \% \^{} \& \_ \{ \} \~{} \textbackslash{} \backslash `

角度符号： `^\circ`

点乘：`\times`

----

''Comments'': `%anything here`

''Multiline Comments'': 

`\usepackage{verbatim}`

```
\begin{comment}
anything 
here
\end{comment}
```

----
''Group''

`{things enclosed here}`

''Environments''

```
\begin{environmentname}
text to be influenced
\end{environmentname}
```

----
''Include Figures''

`\usepackage{graphicx}`

```
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{frog.jpg}
\caption{\label{fig:frog}This frog was uploaded via the project menu.}
\end{figure}
```






Beamer is a Latex class used for creating presentation slides. To create a presentation in beamer is to do it like writing any other document.

----

<<list-links filter:"[tag[Beamer]]">>

----
!!Resources
*[[User Guide|https://www.tug.org/teTeX/tetex-texmfdist/doc/latex/beamer/beameruserguide.pdf]]
*[[Beamer by Examples|http://www.tug.org/pracjourn/2005-4/mertz/mertz.pdf]]
*[[More Examples|http://www2.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/~frank/ENG/latex-course/latex-course-3/latex-course-3_en.html]]
*[[A Tutorial PPT|http://web.mit.edu/rsi/www/pdfs/beamer-tutorial.pdf]]
*[[Wikibook page|https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX/Presentations]]






```
\documentclass{beamer}

\title{Title}
\author{Author}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\begin{frame}
\titlepage
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\tableofcontents
\end{frame}

\section{Name}
\subsection{Name}
\begin{frame}
    \frametitle{Title}
    \framesubtitle{Subtitle}

    Frame Contents.

    \begin{block}{Name}
        Block Contents.
    \end{block}
\end{frame}

\end{document}

```

There are three ways to make a list: itemization, enumeration, description.

----
!!Itemize/Enumerate


```
\begin{itemize/enumerate}
    \item Contents
    \item Contents
\end{itemize/enumerate}
```

*@@color:green;Can nest itemize and enumerate, up to 3 levels.@@ But that may be ugly.
*Can use options to change marker. Itemize: `[triangle/circle/square/ball]`, enumerate: `[circle/square/ball]`.


----
!!Description
```
\begin{description}
\item[Lion] King of the savanna.
\item[Tiger] King of the jungle.
\end{description}

\begin{description}[longest label]
\item<1->[short] Some text.
\item<2->[longest label] Some text.
\item<3->[long label] Some text.
\end{description}
```






*Can set the color of every element: `\setbeamercolor{frametitle}{bg=green!20}`
*`\AtBeginSection{}`
*`\tableofcontents[currentsection]`
*fitting graphic/table: `\resizebox{0.7\linewidth}{!}{content}`
*`\makebox[\linewidth][c]{\begin{tabular}...\end{tabular}}`
*highlight cells in table with tikz






Firstly, one should define a bibliography:

```
\begin{thebibliography}{10}
\bibitem{Goldbach1742}[Goldbach, 1742]
Christian Goldbach.
\newblock A problem we should try to solve before the ISPN ’43 deadline,
\newblock \emph{Letter to Leonhard Euler}, 1742.
\end{thebibliography}
```

Then one can cite: 

```
\begin{block}{Open Questions}
Is every even number the sum of two primes?
\cite{Goldbach1742}
\end{block}
```

 RooPlot * mod2p = model.plotOn(g_frame, Components("argus"));

```
 RooHist * datah = datap->getHist("h_data");

 FormatData(datah);

公共CVS账号：bes3/bes3charm

Modify: cmthome/version/setupCVS.sh


''checkout''

```
cmt cvstags <Package>
```


```
cmt co  -r <tag> <package> 
```

''create a new package''

```
 cd <dev area>
 cmt create <packagename> <version> 
```

*generating src/, cmt/ directories.
*need to modify: cmt/requirement
*can add: share/(independent configs), README, test/(files needed for testing)

''build a package'':

```
>cd cmt
>vi requirements
>cmt config
>source setup.sh
>gmake
```

''Import a new package''

@@color:blue;need personal CVS account@@

Remove unwanted files: unnecessary configs, "x86-" folder

```
cd <package-name>/<version>
cvs import -m 'First import of <package-name>' BossCvs/<package-name> Bes <version>
```

''tag a package''

create a new version folder

```
cvs tag <new-version>
```

!!Phase of Translation

''tranlation unit'': a source file together with its included files.

''translation'': translate units get linked to form an executable program or a dynamic-link library.

''phases'':

*character mapping
*line splicing
*tokenization
*character-set mapping
*string concatenation
*translation
*linkage

----

!!Preprocessor Directives

*`#define`
**`#define identifier token-string`
**`#define identifier(opt1, ... , optn) token-string`
*`#undef`
*`#include`
*`#error`: to prompt an error message
*`#import`
*`#if`, `#elif`, `#else`, `#endif`
**`#if DLEVEL > 5`
*`#using file [as_friend]`: import 
*`#line`: to change the line number and filename stored by the preprocessor
*`#pragma`: Pragma directives specify machine- or operating-specific compiler features. 

----

!!Preprocessor Operators

The operators that can be used in `#define`

*the stringizer `#`:Causes the corresponding actual argument to be enclosed in double quotation marks
*charizing operator `#@`: Causes the corresponding argument to be enclosed in single quotation marks and to be treated as a character (Microsoft Specific)
*token-pasting operator `##`: Allows tokens used as actual arguments to be concatenated to form other tokens
*`defined`

----
!!Standard predefined macros

*`__cplusplus`:Defined as an integer literal value when the translation unit is compiled as C++. Otherwise, undefined.
*`__DATE__`:The compilation date of the current source file. 
*`__FILE__`:The name of the current source file. 
*`__LINE__ `:Defined as the integer line number in the current source file. 
*`__STDC__`: Defined as 1 only when compiled as C and if the /Za compiler option is specified.






https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_function_%28probability_theory%29

----

''Definition'':

#The expected value of $$e^{itX}$$
#Essentially the Fourier transform of the p.d.f.

----

''Uses''

#Basic manipulation of distributions. E.g., getting the distribution of $$\Sigma\alpha_i X_i$$.
#Find the nth moments of a random variable.
#Data analysis: fit probability distribution to samples of data where likelihood procedures are impractical.






| !Class Name |
|attributes |
|operations() |
|responsibilities |

''visibility'': `+` for public, `-` for private, `#` for protected, `~` for package.

''associations'': filled arrow, representing static relationship. 

''multiplicity'': places near the end of an association, indicating the number of instances for this class linked to one instance of the other.(`0..1`, `1`,`0..*`,`1..*` = `*`,`n` means only n)

''constraints'': place inside `{}`

''composition'': filled diamond; `aggregation`: hollow diamond; pointing towards the 'whole' class.

''generalization'': inheritance/"is a".

@@color:green;the aggregate can only access the public member of the part class, while the inheritance can access both the public and protected member of the superclass.@@








!!J/psi and psi(2S) Radiative Transitions to eta_c

ROOT has a C++ interpreter called cling built in. 

*It is used for the prompt, @@color:green;both C++ and Python.@@
*It also serves as a source of information to store C++ objects
*And it provides the back-end for ROOT’s signal/slot and plug-in mechanisms.

----
!!ROOT Prompt

*`?` to show command lists
*Single line command can do without `;`, it makes a difference of whether to output expression value.
*`.>` to redirect output

*There is no way to back up; you are better off writing a script.

----
!!C++ Scripts

!!!Run a Script:

```
root myScript.C
```
or

```
root [] .x myScript.C
root [] .x myScript2.C(12, "A String")

```

or

```
root [] .L myScript.C
root [] myScript()
```

!!!@@color:green;Executing a Script From a Script@@:

```
void cernstaff() {
   if (gSystem->AccessPathName("cernstaff.root")) {
      gROOT->ProcessLine(".x cernbuild.C");
   }
```

A minimum `CMakeLists.txt`

```
cmake_minimum_required (VERSION 2.6)
project (Tutorial)
add_executable(Tutorial tutorial.cxx)
```

*`include_directories("${PROJECT_BINARY_DIR}")`, `add_subdirectory (MathFunctions) `
*`add_library(MathFunctions mysqrt.cxx)`
*`add_executable (Tutorial tutorial.cxx)`
*`install (TARGETS MathFunctions DESTINATION bin)` `install (FILES MathFunctions.h DESTINATION include)`

Simply create a file with the `.py` extension, then you can import it. ''Make sure the file must be created within the directory where the python searches for module''.

```
import sys

sys.path.append(your_path)
```

To permanently change the path, should change the environment variable ''$PYTHONPATH''.

----

!!CUDA C/C++：

''Compute Unified Device Architecture''

*使用GPU大量计算单元和高带宽实现通用计算的计算平台
*提出了对硬件和软件要求

*基本概念：
**异构计算、主机和设备
**关键字
**线程的组织架构，Grid和Block
*内存组织架构

''异构计算：''

*Host（主机）：GPU和它的内存(host memory)
*Device（设备）：GPU和它的内存(device memory)

主机和设备共用一套OS，编程时需要同时考虑。

CPU和GPU的区别：低延迟 vs. 高吞吐量。CPU适合复杂逻辑计算，GPU则有更多的晶体管用于数学计算。

''异构计算代码组成：''

parallel function/code + serial code.

#申请GPU内存
#加载GPU程序，进行计算
#将结果从GPU内存拷回CPU内存，释放GPU内存


''GPU 内存组织''

内存的分配是程序优化的要点：指定内存；thread/block数与程序需要的匹配。

*SM(Streaming Multiprocessor)：小、块
**寄存器内存
**共享内存
**产量内存
**纹理内存/L1缓存
*Global Memory：大、慢


''CUDA 编程模型''

| !硬件 | !软件 |
| Thread | CUDA Core |
| Thread Block | SM |
| Grid（group of blocks) | Device |


----

CUDA 编程实现：

*`nvidia-smi`命令：检查GPU
*`nvcc`：nvidia 编译器
*`cu`作为扩展名结尾
*`nvprof`：检测性能瓶颈

hello world样例程序

```
#include<stdio.h>
#include<cuda_runtime.h>

__global__ void hello(void)
{
printf("hello world!\n");
}

int main()
{
hello<<<1,1>>>();    //调用函数，CPU继续执行之后的命令
cudaDeviceReset();    //重置GPU资源；会等待GPU执行完
cudaDeviceSynchronize();  //同步GPU，会等待GPU执行完毕
return 0;
}
```

''修饰符：''

*`__global__`：表示从host调用，在device执行
*`CC3.x`：主机/设备端调用，设备端执行；对计算能力有要求

`<<<x1,x2>>>`：grid和block的设置

''内存管理''：

*设备指针只能指向设备内存：可以传递，不能取内容
*主机指针只能指向主机内存：可以传递，不能引用
*`cudaMalloc()`,`cudaFree()`,`cudaMemcpy()`为GPU上的对应函数。

[[arxiv:0911.4960|https://arxiv.org/abs/0911.4960]]

This paper will discuss the design and construction of BESIII, which is designed to study physics in the tau-charm energy region utilizing the new high luminosity BEPCII double ring e+e- collider. The expected performance will be given based on Monte Carlo simulations and results of cosmic ray and beam tests. In BESIII, tracking and momentum measurements for charged particles are made by a cylindrical multilayer drift chamber in a 1 T superconducting solenoid. Charged particles are identified with a time-of-flight system based on plastic scintillators in conjunction with dE/dx (energy loss per unit pathlength) measurements in the drift chamber. Energies of electromagnetic showers are measured by a CsI(Tl) crystal calorimeter located inside the solenoid magnet. Muons are identified by arrays of resistive plate chambers in the steel magnetic flux return. The level 1 trigger system, Data Acquisition system and the event filter system based on networked computers will also be described.

*PHOKHARA simulates $$e^+e^-$$ collision into a hadronic final states with a energetic ISR photon.
*EKHARA studies the processes
*PHOKHARA has NLO accuracy, while EKHARA has LO accuracy.

''particle properties'' 

*defined in evt.pdl

''decay tables''

*defined in DECAY.DEC, use particle info in evt.pdl
*use `alias` to create varied version of a particle
*`ChargeConj`
*make an empty decay list to make a particle stable.

''Algorithm''

*calculate with decay amplitude
*accept-reject algorithm on the phase space
*refinement to solve the problem of prob-calculation and efficiency

''Decay Models''

*`EvtDecayBase`: `EvtDecayAmp`, `EvtDecayProb`, `EvtDecayIncoherent`

!!Basics

[[Fortran Example 1]]



*`c`/`!` means comments
*Fortran is not case-sensitive
*Column position rules: Col. 7-72 : Statements

----
!!Variables

```
     integer   list of variables
      real      list of variables
      double precision  list of variables
      complex   list of variables
      logical   list of variables
      character list of variables
```

''parameter'': const `parameter (pi = 3.14159)`

Assignment: `variable_name = expression`

----
!!Logical Expressions

*`.LT.` less than ...
*`.TRUE.`
*`.AND.`


----
!!Flow Control

''If then''

```
 if (x .GT. 0) then
         if (x .GE. y) then
            write(*,*) 'x is positive and x >= y'
         else
            write(*,*) 'x is positive but x 
```

''do loop'': for loop

```
      integer i, n, sum
 
      sum = 0
      do 10 i = 1, n
         sum = sum + i
         write(*,*) 'i =', i
         write(*,*) 'sum =', sum
  10  continue
```

Also: while-loop, until-loop

----
!!Array

*`real a(20)`: a[20]
*` real b(0:19), weird(-162:237)`: arbitrary index range
*`real A(3,5)`: two dimensional

----
!!Functions

```
      abs     absolute value
      min     minimum value
      max     maximum value
      sqrt    square root
      sin     sine
      cos     cosine
      tan     tangent
      atan    arctangent
      exp     exponential (natural)
      log     logarithm (natural)
```

*Functions have a type. This type must also be declared in the calling program.
*The return value should be stored in a variable with the same name as the function.
*Functions are terminated by the return statement instead of stop.

!!Subroutines

```
      subroutine iswap (a, b)
      integer a, b
c Local variables
      integer tmp

      tmp = a
      a = b
      b = tmp

      return
      end
```

*''call-by-reference'':传指针到subroutine，可以改动参数的值

----
!!Common Block

`common /coeff/ alpha, beta` 类似于class

----
!!Data Statement
定义常数
`data list-of-variables/ list-of-values/, ...`

----
!!File I/O

`open (list-of-specifiers)`

Specifiers:

```
    [UNIT=]  u
    IOSTAT=  ios
    ERR=     err
    FILE=    fname
    STATUS=  sta
    ACCESS=  acc
    FORM=    frm
    RECL=    rl
```

[[FILE I/O|Fortran Example 2]]


!!Simple I/O

```
      read (unit no, format no) list-of-variables
      write(unit no, format no) list-of-variables
```

Or simplified as:

```
      read (*,*) list-of-variables
      write(*,*) list-of-variables
```
The first statement will read values from the standard input and assign the values to the variables in the variable list, while the second one writes to the standard output.

----
!!Format Statement

Format options like: how many decimals places in real numbers...

```
      write(*, label) list-of-variables
 label format format-code
```

```
      write(*, 900) i, x
  900 format (I4,F8.3)
```

```
   A - text string
   D - double precision numbers, exponent notation
   E - real numbers, exponent notation
   F - real numbers, fixed point format
   I - integer
   X - horizontal skip (space)
   / - vertical skip (newline)
```








```
      program circle
      real r, area
 
c This program reads a real number r and prints
c the area of a circle with radius r.
 
      write (*,*) 'Give radius r:'
      read  (*,*) r
      area = 3.14159*r*r
      write (*,*) 'Area = ', area
 
      stop
      end
```






```
      program inpdat
c
c  This program reads n points from a data file and stores them in 
c  3 arrays x, y, z.
c
      integer nmax, u
      parameter (nmax=1000, u=20)
      real x(nmax), y(nmax), z(nmax)

c  Open the data file
      open (u, FILE='points.dat', STATUS='OLD')

c  Read the number of points
      read(u,*) n
      if (n.GT.nmax) then
         write(*,*) 'Error: n = ', n, 'is larger than nmax =', nmax
         goto 9999
      endif

c  Loop over the data points
      do 10 i= 1, n
         read(u,100) x(i), y(i), z(i)
   10 enddo
  100 format (3(F10.4))

c  Close the file
      close (u)

c  Now we should process the data somehow...
c  (missing part)

 9999 stop
      end
```

''Design goal'': insulate users from irrevelant details of the software system.

''Base Classes''

*~DataObject
*Algorithm
*Converter

''The four main services for algorithm:''

*The event data store
**`IDataProviderSvc`: allow alg to access/add data in the store
**`IDataManagerSvc`: clear data before a new event
*The detector data store
*The histogram service
*The message service
**`IProperty` interface
**`IMessageSvc` interface

"interface" here means a pure virtual c++ class.


''The three basic methods for an Gaudi Alg'': `initialize()`, `execute()`, `finalize()`

!!GAUDI — A software architecture and framework for building HEP data processing applications

https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0010465501002545






You may wish to execute some
algorithms only for specific types of event, or you may wish to “loop” over an algorithm’s
execute method. 

```
Algorithm* m_pSubAlgorithm; // Pointer to the sub algorithm
// Must be a member variable of the parent class
std::string type; // Type of sub algorithm
std::string name; // Name to be given to subAlgorithm
StatusCode sc; // Status code returned by the call
sc = createSubAlgorithm(type, name, Algorithm*& m_pSubAlgorithm);
```


If a common sub-algorithm should be shared among many different parental algorithms, you should make an [[Tool|Gaudi: Tool]] out of it.






https://lhcb-comp.web.cern.ch/lhcb-comp/Frameworks/Gaudi/Tutorial/7_Using_and_Writing_Tools.pdf






[[GBDT Primer|http://tullo.ch/articles/gradient-boosted-decision-trees-primer/]]

Supervised learning problem.

*given labeled feature vector (x,y)
*seek to estimate a function F^^^^^(x), which approximates true mapping F*. With F* minimizing the expected loss L(y,F(x))
*The model assumes an additive expansion $$F(x,\beta,\alpha)= \sum_{i=1}^n\beta_{i}h(x,\alpha_i)$$, where h is the weak learner. 
*@@color:green;The predictor from gradient boosting is a linear combination of weak learners.@@

The procedure:

*compute $$\beta_m$$, the weight of a given classifier
*weight the training example, to compute the i-th weak classifier.

''动词的人称变化''

| !ich | lerne | arbeite | heiße | bin | habe |
| !du | lernst | arbeitest | heißt | bist | hast |
| !er/sie/es | lernt | arbeitet | heißt | ist | hat |
| !wir | lernen | arbeiten | heißen | sind | haben |
| !ihr | lernt | arbeitet | heißt | seid | habt |
| !sie/Sie | lernen | arbeiten | heißen | sind | haben |

强变化动词：2，3人称单数的词干元音变化


----

''名词的变格''

| !N | !G | !D | !A |
| der | des | dem | den |
| das | des | dem | das |
| die | der | der | die |
| die | der | den | die |

*阳性，中性名词第三格词尾加-e：am Tage, auf dem Lande, nach Hause
*阳中性名词第二格词尾加-s
*复数第三格加-n

----

''形容词词尾变化''

形容词弱变化： der/die/das/die, dieser/jener/solcher, all-

|  | !m. | !n. | !f. | !pl. |
| !N | -e | -e | -e | -en |
| !G | -en | -en | -en | -en |
| !D | -en | -en | -en | -en |
| !A | -en | -e | -e | -en |

|  | !m. | !n. | !f. | !pl. |
| !N | der fleißige Schüler | die fleißige Studentin | das fleißige Kind | die fleißigen Kinder |
| !G | des fleißigen Schülers | der fleißigen Studentin | des fleißigen Kindes | der fleißigen Kinder |
| !D | dem fleißigen Schüler | der fleißigen Studentin | dem fleißigen Kind | den fleißigen Kindern |
| !A | den fleißigen Schüler | die fleißige Studentin | das fleißige Kind | die fleißigen Kinder |

混合变化：ein, kein, mein

|  | !m. | !n. | !f. | !pl. |
| !N | -er | -e | -es | -en |
| !G | -en | -en | -en | -en |
| !D | -en | -en | -en | -en |
| !A | -en | -e | -es | -en |

强变化：无冠词

|  | !m. | !n. | !f. | !pl. |
| !N | -er | -e | -es | -e |
| !G | -en | -er | -en | -er |
| !D | -em | -er | -em | -en |
| !A | -en | -e | -es | -e |

A distributed version control system.

*[[github]]
*[[gitlab]]

----
''git commands''

*`git config`: setup name and emails to be used with commits
**`git config -global user.name "[name]"`
**`git config -global user.email "[email address]"`
*`git init [repository name]`: start a new repository
*`git clone [url]`
*`git add [file]`: adds a file to the staging area
*`git commit -m "[type the message here]"`
*`git commit -a`: commit files added and that have been changed
*`git diff`: show the file differences that are not staged
*`git diff -staged`:show the differences between the files in the staging area and the latest version present
*`git diff [branch1] [branch2]`
*`git reset [file]`: unstage the file, preserve the contents
*`git reset [commit]`: undoes all the commits after the mentioned commit(preserve the changes locally)
*`git reset -hard [commit]`: discard all history and goes back to the specific commit
*`git status`: list files to be committed
*`git rm [file]`: delete the file from the working directory and stage the deletion
*`git log`: list the version history for current branch
*`git log -follow [file]`: lists version history for a file
*`git show [commit]`: shows the metadata and content change of the commit
*`git tag [commitID]`: give tags to the specific commit
*`git branch`: lists all the local branches in the current repository
*`git branch [branch name]`: create a new branch
*`git branch -d [branch name]`: delete a branch
*`git checkout [branch name]`: move to the branch
*`git checkout -b [branch name]`: create a branch and switch to it
*`git merge [branch name]`: merge the specific branch into the current one
*`git remote add [variable name] [remote server link]`: connect local repository to the server
*`git push [variable name] [branch]`
*`git push -all [variable name]`
*`git pull [Repository link]`: fetch and merge changes







A site for version control system.

#[[https://guides.github.com/activities/hello-world/]]: a beginner guide
#[[https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/]]: how to work with Fork & Pull Model

*name the repository `your_username.github.io`

!!Lesson 1

A walkthrough of history.

''3 spectroscopies'': Atomic, nuclear, and hadronic.

''QCD "dilemma"'': from asymptotic freedom to confinement, from perturbative to non-perturbative.

''QCD Lagrangian'': how to get

High Energy Physics: strange particles and above!

''Quantum Numbers: '' P, C, I, G, S, L, J

''How did we get the spin/parity of particles?'' 

Cross Section Measurements, Landau-Yang Theorem, etc.

@@color:green;''Proving Landau-Yang Theorem: ''@@ https://journals.aps.org/pr/pdf/10.1103/PhysRev.77.242

''Examining Dalitz Plot'': 

*Only two variables in three-body decay, so plot into them. 
*Angular correlation of products means uneven distribution of events.
*Resonances should results in lines.

!!Lesson 2

''Dalitz Plot''：

*从三体运动学相空间出发；
*Line pattern -> spin（衰变振幅 -> 勒让德多项式；0=线，1=翅形，2=糖状）
*跨线：干涉的相长相消(constructive/destructive interference)符号变化
*Dalitz Plot Symmetry: 例$$p\bar{p} \rightarrow 3\pi^0 $$
*Dalitz公式： cosTheta与质量的关系
*Fermi Golden Rule?
*Extract Resonances through ML over P=$$\frac{|M|^2*\epsilon}{\int |M|^2*\epsilon}$$

!!Abstract

This review presents an overview of the remarkable progress in the field of heavy-quark exotic hadrons over the past 15 years. It seeks to be pedagogical rather than exhaustive, summarizing both the progress and specific results of experimental discoveries, and the variety of theoretical approaches designed to explain these new states.

!Higher Charmonia

Written in Feburary, 2008

[[Document|https://arxiv.org/pdf/hep-ph/0505002.pdf]]

----

!!Introduction

''Why Charmonium is Interesting:''

#Below open charm DD Threshold(3.73 ~GeV): experimentally clear spectrum of narrow states, can be predicted by potential model
#spin-dependent interquark forces are evident in the splitting of states within multiplets; agreeing with a OGE hamiltonian
#qualitatively different types of resonances are expected at higher Charmonia.

@@color:#3C3C8A; further reading on theoretical motivation [7] to [13].@@

''Remarkable Experiment Results''

#$$\eta_{c}'$$
#X(3872) 
#P wave singlet: h,,c,,;  


''Topics:''

#Search for $$\phi_{2}(1^{3}D_{2}), \eta_{c2}(1^{1}D_2)$$:
#Test the Lorentz Nature of Confinement: multiplet splitting of orbittally-excited ccbar states.
#search for exotica such as hybrids: the lightest ccbar hybrid may lie near 4.4GeV(LGT, lattice gauge theory)
#mixing between quark model qqbar basis states and two-messon continua. Study ccbar system to understand the effect of @@color:green; "unquenching the quark model"@@(including meson loops).

''What the author did: ''

*a theoretical study of expected properties of charmonium states, especially above DD threshold
*Two Models: a conventional unrelativistic model; and the Godfrey-Isgur relativied potential model.
*All states: 1-4S, 1-3P, 1-2D, 1-2F, 1G
*quantities: spectrum; E1(and some M1) EM transition rates; strong partial and total widths above OCT.

----
!!Spectrum

!!!@@color:#008090;Nonrelativistic potential model@@

*Schroedinger function
*potential model: standard color Coulomb, linear scalar form, a Gaussian-smeared contact hyperfine interaction in 0th potential.

@@color:orange;spin-spin contact hyperfine interaction@@, a spin-dependent term predicted by OGE force. Remaining spin-dependent terms treated as mass shifts using LO perturbation theory.

''Input: ''

*(alpha_s, b, m_c, sigma)  @@color:green; the four parameters for the central potential,@@ obtained through fitting the spectrum of known states.
*11 Known States: J/psi, eta_c, eta_c', psi', psi(4040, 3S), psi(4415, 4S) Xcj(0,1,2), psi(3770, 1D), psi(4159, 2D)

!!!@@color:#008090;Godfrey-Isgur relativized potential model@@
''a “relativized” extension'' of the previous nonrelativistic model.

*assuming a relativistic dispersion relation
*a QCD-motivated running coupling
*a flavor-dependent potential smearing parameter
*replaces factors of quark mass with quark kinetic energy

性能： ''reasonably accurate results for the spectrum and matrix elements of quarkonia of all u, d, s, c, b quark flavors'', whereas the 1st model is only fitted to the ccbar system.

!!!@@color:#008090;Discussion:@@

More input from D, F, G wave states would be very helpful.

----
!!Radiative Transitions
!!!@@color:#008090;E1 Transitions@@

*precious pathway between charmoniums of different quantum numbers.
*typical width: 10s to 100s ~KeV

''E1 radiative partial widths公式''：spatial矩阵元含有初末态波函数，从而模型依赖

Important transitions: from 1^^- -^^ (to 2P, 3P); 1D3^^-^^ and 2^^-^^ (to 1P) 

!!!@@color:#008090;M1 Transitions@@

*rather weaker than E1;
*allow access to spin-singlets states otherwise hard to produce
*serious disagreement on transition rates between Theo/Exp

M1 radiative partial widths公式: bad correction to the wavefunctions and recoil effects

Needs more data to improve the discription.

----
!!Open-Flavor Strong Decays
!!!@@color:#008090;Decay Model@@
''Transition to open-flavor states'': 

*production of qqbar(u,d,s), separation into two open-charm mesons. 
*The dominating strong decays.
*Underlying QCD mechanism poorly understood.
*phenomenological qqbar production amplitude model: 3P0, extended to meson and baryon @@color:green;author used this one@@
*another model: qqbar production amplitude as the time component of a Lorentz vector

!!!@@color:#008090;Charmonium Decays@@
''Earlier results:'' Psi(3770), Psi(4040), Psi(4415) calculated in the original model.

''In this study:''

*Foundd all the kinematically allowed open-flavor decays modes, calculated partial width and strong decay amplitudes.
*3P0 model, 简谐振子(SHO) wavefunction, width decided by comparing two models' overlap
*tested parameter accuracy with psi(3770), psi(4040), psi(4159), and psi(4415)

The DP mixing angle in D1, D1'

----
!!Discussion of ccbar States

@@color:#008090;''psi(3770)''@@

3D1, perhaps with a 2^^3^^S1 component.

if pure 3D1 state: width=43 ~MeV. exp_width=23.6 ~MeV, so ''has mixing instead''. mixing angle should be -17.4 degree.

partial width ratio of (ee->psi3770)/(ee->psi3686): 0.10 theoretical, 0.12 experimental


@@color:#008090;''psi(4040)''@@

*Four modes allowed: DD, D*D, D*D*, ~DsDs.
*Reportedly, D*0D*0>>D*0D0>>D0D0. So D*D* molecule? @@color:green;Predicted by 3P0 model.@@
*Can be used to access 2P ccbar multiplets.
*D*D* Interesting: 3 independent amplitudes


@@color:#008090;''psi(4159)''@@

*2^^3^^D1, maybe with significant components
*five modes:  DD, D*D, D*D*, ~DsDs, ~DsDs*

@@color:green;A determination of these D∗D∗ decay amplitude ratios would be an interesting test of decay models. @@

@@color:#008090;''psi(4415)''@@

*4^^3^^S1. But ccbar hybrids may start appearing near the mass region
*10 Decay modes. 
*''Width'' disagreements in PDG/BES/this theory.
*important modes: DD1, DD2*, D*D*
*May provide access to Ds(2317)

@@color:#008090;''3S and 4S States''@@

*assigned: potential model masses 4043 ~MeV and 4384 ~MeV.
*get widths 80 ~MeV and 61 ~MeV respectively
*May be observable in γγ and hadronic production

@@color:#008090;''2P States''@@

* mass predicted around 3.95 ~GeV; disagreement of GI/NR Model on mass spliting.
* 2^^3^^P0 Chi0(3852), 2^^3^^P1 Chi1(3925) and 2^^1P^^1 hc(3934)

@@color:green;Observation of the D/S ratio in a DD∗ enhancement could be a useful check of the assumption of a resonant 1+ cc¯ contribution.@@

@@color:#008090;''3P States''@@

*mass predicted around 4.3 ~GeV
*3^^1^^P1 hc(4279),  3^^3^^P2 Xc2(4317)
* may produce from psi(4415) E1 transition

@@color:#008090;''1D States''@@

*^^3^^D3 Psi(3806), may decay to gXc2
*Production mechanism: C=(-) can't come from gg or glgl fusion. But may from 2^^3^^P2

@@color:#008090;''2D States''@@

*2^^3^^D1 candidate Psi(4159).
*total width ranging from ~78 MeV to 148 ~MeV.
*If can be produced, can test strong decay amplitudes.

@@color:#008090;''1F States''@@

*4025/4095 ~GeV
*Produce: Psi(4159) E1 to ^^3^^F2 Xc2
*Can be used to produce narrow 1D states


@@color:#008090;''2F and 1G States''@@

*hard to test with experiments.
*2F mean mass 4350(NR)/4425(GI), 1G mean mass 4225(NR)/4320(GI).
* width ranging from 58 to 180 ~MeV.

----
!!Summary 

*Computed spectrum, all allowed E1 and some M1 transition partial width
*Should be useful in identifying new states; Lorentz structure of confinements; and the nature of spin-dependent forces.
*Important states: Psi(3770), Psi(4040), Psi(4415)
*Higher Charmonia is important also because qualitatively different types of resonances are expected at these masses.






https://research.cs.wisc.edu/htcondor/

A workload management system for compute-intensive jobs.

*[[IHEP Condor]]
*[[Quick start guide|https://research.cs.wisc.edu/htcondor/manual/quickstart.html]]
*[[A more detailed guide|http://research.iac.es/sieinvens/siepedia/pmwiki.php?n=HOWTOs.Condor]]
*[[FAQ|https://htcondor-wiki.cs.wisc.edu/index.cgi/wiki?p=HowToAdminRecipes]]
*[[Installation, start up, shut down, reconfiguration|https://htcondor.readthedocs.io/en/v8_9_2/admin-manual/installation-startup-shutdown-reconfiguration.html]]






----
!!基本操作

1. ''设置环境变量''：

建议直接修改~/.bashrc或是~/.tcshrc

a. 在lxslc6.ihep.ac.cn:
tcsh shell 设置命令:   

`setenv PATH /afs/ihep.ac.cn/soft/common/sysgroup/hep_job/bin:${PATH}
`

bash shell 设置命令:  

`export PATH=/afs/ihep.ac.cn/soft/common/sysgroup/hep_job/bin:$PATH` 

b. 在lxslc5.ihep.ac.cn:

tcsh shell设置命令: 

`setenv PATH /afs/ihep.ac.cn/soft/common/sysgroup/hep_job/bin5:${PATH}`

bash shell设置命令: 

`export PATH=/afs/ihep.ac.cn/soft/common/sysgroup/hep_job/bin5:$PATH `



2.'' 提交作业''：

方式一： 

*替换`boss -q joboption`为 `boss.condor  joboption`

方式二：

*替换 `qsub -q besq jobscript.sh`为`hep_sub -g physics jobscript.sh` (@@color:green;jobscript.sh  要有可执行权限@@)
*` [-o OUT]`,`[-e ERROR]`, `[-l LOG]`,指定输出，报错和日志。输出和报错默认`./jobscript.sh.out/err`，日志默认不产生
*`[-argu ARGUMENTS [ARGUMENTS ...]]`



3. ''查询作业：''

*`hep_q -u username`


4. ''删除作业''：

*`hep_rm jobid`
*`hep_rm -a`
*[[批量删作业脚本|bash_example1]]

!!Binomial distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution

B(n,p), mean = np, variance = npq.

----

!!Multinomial distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_distribution

M(n,p1, p2, ...), mean(i) = np, variance = npq.

!!Poisson distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution

P(n,n_exp). Multinomial when the p(n) array becomes a continuum.

加法定理。

----

!!Exponential distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution

----

!!Uniform distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_distribution_(continuous)

----

!!Gamma Distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_distribution

Two parameters: alpha, beta. 

mean=alpha/beta, V=alpha/(beta^2)

----
!!Gaussian Distribution

FWHM=2.355 sigma

!!Chisquare Distribution
The sum of n standard gaussians.

Parameter: degree of freedom. 
加法定理。

----
!!Breit-Wigner Distribution
The distribution of invariant mass.

加法定理。

----
!!t Distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution


*One parameter: degree of freedom. 
*When n goes from 0 to infinity, the distribution goes from Breit-Wigner to Gaussian.
*The distribution of Gaussian/sqrt(Chisquare).

!!F Distribution
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-distribution

*Two parameters: n1, n2
*The distribution of Chisquare(n1)/Chisquare(n2).

#[ext[Issues and Opportunities in Exotic Hadrons|./materials/documents/WhitePaper.pdf]]: 2015

```

!!Measurement of B(J/psi->eta_c gamma) at KEDR

https://arxiv.org/abs/1012.1694






[[PDG Documents|http://pdg.lbl.gov/2016/reviews/rpp2016-rev-kinematics.pdf]]

----
*Lorentz Transformation
*E,,cm,,, $$\beta_{cm}$$(velocity), 
*''Lorentz-invariant amplitudes'': 
For the matrix elements of scattering or decay processes. $$M'$$

*''Particle Decays'': 

$$d\tau=\frac{(2\pi)^{4}}{2M}|M|^{2}d\Phi_{n}(P;p_{1},...,p_{n})$$, where $$d\Phi_{n}$$ is an element of n-body phase space.

*Survival Probability: exponential;

*''Two-body decays:''

$$E_{1}=\frac{M^{2}-m_{2}^{2}-m_{1}^{2}}{2M}$$,

$$|p_{1}|=|p_{2}|=\frac{[(M^{2}-(m_{1}+m_{2})^{2})(M^{2}-(m_{1}-m_{2})^{2})]^{1/2}}{2M},$$

$$d\tau=\frac{1}{32\pi^{2}}|M'|^{2}\frac{p_{1}}{M^{2}}d\Omega$$

*''Three-body decays:''

$$d\tau=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{5}}\frac{1}{16M}|M'|^{2}dE_{1}dE_{2}d\alpha d(cos\beta) d\gamma$$,

or $$d\tau=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{5}}\frac{1}{16M^{2}}|M'|^{2}|p_{1}^{*}|p_{3}|dm_{12}d\Omega^{*}_{1}d\Omega_{3}$$

If the decaying particle is a scalar, or we average over its spin states, then the integration over the angles in Eq.(first $$d\tau$$) gives:

$$d\tau=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{3}}\frac{1}{8M}\overline{|M'|^{2}}dE_{1}dE_{2}=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{3}}\frac{1}{32M^{3}}\overline{|M'|^{2}}dm_{12}^{2}dm_{23}^{2} $$

*''Dalitz Plots:''

$$m_{12}^{2} \, vs.  \, m_{23}^{2}$$. Can be used to check if $$|M'|^{2}$$ is constant. Bands indicate decay chains.

*@@color:green;''Partial Waves''@@
*''Transverse Variables''

!The Basics
*`pwd`
*`cd`: `cd -` to previous folder, `cd ~username` change to user's home dir.
*`ls`: `-l` list detailed info, `-a` show hidden files
*`cp`
*`mv`
*`rm`:`-f` force removing,
*`mkdir`
*`du`: print used space, `-c` total space, `-m` use mb as unit.
*`chmod`: `chmod g+x file`, `chmod 755 file`, 
*`chown user file`: change the ownership of the file to the user.
*`less`: view text files as well as standard output. E.g. `ls | less`.
*`passwd`: change user password
*`head/tail -n file`: print the first/last n lines of a file.
*`echo`: print string to screen. `-e` to allow [[Execution of Backslash]]. 
*`touch`
*`date`: print current time
*`df`: display disk space usage for all
*`seq 1 100`: print a sequence; `-w` to put 0s in front
*`sz` to send file, `rz` to receive file.

!Shell Scripts
*[[Bash Scripts]]







`awk '/search_pattern/ { action_to_take_on_matches; another_action; }' file_to_parse`

*default action = `print`
*`{print $2}`: print the 2nd field; default field separater is blank space.


Examples:

*`awk -F':' '{ print $1 }' /etc/passwd`
*`awk '$9 == 500 { print $0}' /var/log/httpd/access.log`
*`awk "NR==1{print;exit}" /etc/resolv.conf`
*`awk '{total += $1} END {print total}' earnings.txt`: simple arithmatic
*`awk 'BEGIN {printf "%.3f\n", 2005.50 / 3}'`: awk can calculate floating point number







!!cat
cat means to concatenate. It can be used to combine text files.

*`cat filename`: display the content of the file
*`cat file1 file2 file3 ... > newfile`: combine the files into a new one, original files are not changed.
*`cat file1 file2 >> newfile`: to append the content to the newfile
*`-b`: to number unblank lines.
*`-n`: to number all lines.
*`-s`: to squeeze adjacent blank lines






!!cut
Remove sections from each line of a file.

*`cut -d ":" -f 1 filename`: get the content before `:` in each line; `d` for delimiter, `f` for fields to select.
*`cut -c 4-10 filename`: characters in [4,10]; `4,10` means {4,10}, `10-` means [10,end]
*`-s, --only-delimited`: Don't print lines without delimiter







*`diff file1 file2`: show difference of two files
*`vimdiff file1 file2`: open vim and vsplit, showing difference of two files.






!!find

Find the files according to the filters.

*`find folder -name filename`: find the file by the name
*`-iname`:case insensitive
*`-type df`: `d` for directory, `f` for file
*`-perm 777`: permission
*`-exec`: execute command for the files
*`-empty`:empty files
*`-mtime`: last modified time(day), things like `-mtime +50 -mtime -100` for a range
*`-atime`: last access time(day)
*`-cmin -60`:changed within an hour
*`-size`:parameters like `+50m`,`-1000k`

!!Change Filename Patterns for a Group of Files.

Firstly, run this command to check if your setting is right.

```
for x in ./*; do echo $x === Will Become === `echo $x|sed 's/old_pat/new_pat/g'`; done
```

After the check, change `echo` to `mv`, and remove `=== Will Become ===`

!!Show if the log file succeeded

```
for x in ./*bosslog; do echo $x ...... `cat $x | tail -2 | head -1 `; done
```








!!grep

Search for the text files, and print the lines that contains the pattern. 

*`grep string filename` : print the lines that contains the string.
*`-x`: exact  line match
*`-v`: reverse match
*`-i`: case insensitive
*`-r`: search children folders
*`-f`: use each line of the file as a pattern
*`-l`: just list the path of the file
*`grep 'a\|b' filename`: grep a or b
*`grep -E 'a|b' filename`: grep a or b, through regex
*`grep -E 'a.*b' filename`: grep a and b, through regex
*`grep a filename| grep b`: grep a and b
*`--include <pattern>`: to put restriction on the filenames






!!Running Multiple Commands

Execute commands sequentially:

`command1; command2; command3 ...`: 

Conditional running:

`command1 && command2`: only run command2 if command1 successed

@@color:green;Passing output:@@

`command1 | command2`: the output of command1 would be the input of command2. [[More about pipes|linux_pipes]]






*`>`: overwrite the output to a file
*`>>`: append the output to a file
*`command1 | command2`: use the output of command1 as the input of command2
*`< file`: use the content of the file as the input of the first command
*`<<value`: value is passed to the input of the first command

Commands that can use pipes

*`... | head -n`: show the first n lines
*`... | tail -n`: show the last n lines
*`sort `: sort the order, `-r/n/f/b/R`: reverse/numeric/ignore case/ignore leading blanks/random sequence but grouped.
*`uniq`: print unique lines in a ''sorted'' file.  `-u/d/c`: show unique/show repeated/count
*`wc -l`: count the number of lines
*`rev`: reverse the order
*`tr source_charlist translated_charlist`: translate






!!Quotes

*` " " `: Anything enclosed is removed the meaning of the characters (except \ and $).
*` ' ' `: Even \ and $ are not affected.
*`` ` ` ``:To execute the command.







!!sed
Stream EDitor, used for modifying files in unix/linux.

*`sed '' file.txt`: simply print the file.
*`sed 's/search_pattern/replacement_string/' file.txt`: replace the text in a file, by default only replace the 1st occurance in each line.
* `-i`: to make the change ''in place'', otherwise it doesn't modify the files.
*`sed 's/search_pattern/replacement_string/2' file.txt`: replace the nth occurance in each line.
*`sed 's/search_pattern/replacement_string/g' file.txt`: global replacement.
*`sed 's/search_pattern/replacement_string/3g' file.txt`: global replacement starting from the nth occurance.
*`sed 's_http://_www_' file.txt`: can use `_` or `|` as delimiters instead of `/`.
*when used in the replacement_string, `&` represents the matched string.
*`sed 's/\(str_part1\)\(str_part2\)/\2\1/' file.txt`: switch the two parts of the strings.
*`-n`: print only replaced lines
*`sed_command_1 | sed_command_2`: run multiple sed commands
*`sed -e option_1 -e option_2 file.txt`: another way to run multiple sed commands
*`sed 'line_number s/search/replace/' file.txt`: specifying line numbers, with things like `3`, `1,3`, `2,$`
*`sed '/pattern1/ s/search_pattern/replacement/' file.txt`: replace on lines that match pattern1
*`sed 'line_number d' file.txt`: delete lines
*`sed '/pattern/ a the_line_to_add' file.txt`: add a line after matches
*`sed '/pattern/ i the_line_to_add' file.txt`: add a line before matches
*`sed '/pattern/ c the_changed_line' file.txt`: change matched lines
*`sed` 结合 `grep -rl`可以完成目录中全部文件的关键字替换。






An apparently statistically significant observation may have actually arisen by chance because of the size of the parameter space to be searched.

''Divide the threshold of p-value by the number of multiple tests.''

*https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Look-elsewhere_effect
*https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_comparisons_problem
*https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonferroni_correction
*[[Trial factors for the look elsewhere effect in high energy physics|https://arxiv.org/pdf/1005.1891.pdf]]

!!LCIO

http://lcio.desy.de/v02-09/doc/manual_html/manual.html

''LCIO packages''

*EVENT: 	The base interfaces of all data classes in LCIO. To be used for reading existing data.
*IO: The base interfaces for io of data.
*IMPL: The (default) implementations of the base interfaces that are defined in EVENT. Needed for writing new data or extending existing data, e.g. during reconstruction.
*UTIL: Holds convenient and support classes and methods for the LCIO objects.
*lcio: The namespace lcio combines EVENT, IO, UTIL and IMPL for user convenience (#include "lcio.h").

[img[./img/HEPCC/LCIO_EDM.png]]

[img[./img/HEPCC/LCIO_EDE.png]]

''Data Format'': use SIO(serial IO) format

----

!!PODIO

[[PODIO introduction paper]]

PODIO is a C ++ library that supports the automatic creation of event data models
(EDMs) and efficient I/O code for HEP experiments. It is developed as a new EDM Toolkit for
future particle physics experiments in the context of the AIDA2020 EU programme.

''POD'': plain old data

*scalar type
*class type(trivial, standard layout, has no non-static members that are non-POD)
*an array of such types

''the 3 POD layers''

*POD layer: the arrays of the actual data structures
*object layer:  transient, lightweight objects which handle the relations between
the individual objects in the EDM
*user layer:  handles to the EDM object, and collections of EDM
object handles

''object ownership'': avoiding unclear object ownership and memory leaks. (object ownership: the pointer that point to the object)

here it's handled in the object layer, at two stages.

*before registering data objects with an event store they are reference counted and garbage
collected
*after registering with the event store the ownership is transferred to the event store which
handles the object lifetime

''code generation''

PODIO creates all C ++ and Python code for the users based on a description of the EDM
structures in a [[yaml]] file

EDM data structures:

*basic type data members
*components (structs of basic types)
*references to other objects

Python is treated as first class citizen in PODIO, i.e. one can use pythonic code for iterators
etc.

''Relatio between objects''

*pointers are converted to collection indices by introducing a dedicated ~ObjectID

''Vectorization''

~SoA(struct of arrays) layout better than ~AoS, to make better use of vector instructions.

''I/O''

currently mainly use ROOT I/O. But can improve with special design to make use of POD.








!!Gaudi developer guide:

```

Gaudi developer guide:
	Architecture design document: ref.1(LHCb 98-064 COMP)

	units:	same as in GEANT4/CLHEP
		CLHEP/Units/SystemOfUnits.h
	
	coding convention: ref 6.(LHCb 2001-054 COMP)
		.h/.cpp
		.opts(job options files)
		.py
		name convention:
			histograms placed in named subdirs of the transient histogram store
			
	architecture design:
		insulate users from irrelevant details:		libraries for I/O, graphics...
		
		3 base classes:
			DataObject
			Algorithm
			Converter
			
		components: service, algorithm
			
		important interfaces to an algorithm
			-IAlgorithm, IProperty, IDataProviderSvc, ISvcLocator, IMessageSvc, IHistogramSvc, ...
			-only write: initialize(), execute(), finalize()
			-interface/implements:		
				pure virtual class/its inheritance
				multiple inheritance problem is avoided?
				
		algorithm scheduling:
			EventLoopMgr service
			
	Event Store:
		IDataProviderSvc interface:
			findObject, retrieveObject, registerObject
		Object container:
			-ObjectVector<T>, ObjectList<T>.
			-can contain those that're not inherited from DataObject class
			-points to but not hold the objects
			-containers are treated like a single DataObject by the interface.
				the design is to make fewer accesses to bigger objects instead
			-ContainedObject base class
			
			an object can only belong to a single container, to avoid lifetime issues
				-automatically done when push_back to a second container
			
			checklist:
				-don't delete objects that one has registered
				-don't delete objects that are contained within an object
				-don't register local objects (not created with new)
				-don't delete objects which you got from the store via findObjects() / retrieveObjects()
				-delete objects created with new, and not registered into a store
			
		SmartDataPtr/SmartDataLocator
			a normal C++ pointer having a constructor
			
		persistent store: data for later use
			
			
	Creating service:
		define interfaces
		derive the concrete service class from the Service base class
		implement the queryInterface() method
		implement initialize()
		
	Tools and ToolSvc
		AlgTool base class
		
		necessary code:
			define the specific interface: inheriting from the IAlgTool interface
			derive the tool class from the AlgTool base class
			provide the constructor
			declare the additional interface
			implement the factory adding the lines of code
			implement the specific interface methods
			
	Assosiator: allow user to navigate between any two arbitrary classes in the Event Model using the same interface
	
	Gaudi job option script with python

	AIDA: ref 10.(htttps://aida.freehep.org)

	
```

''Reading all branches of a tree.''

```
import ROOT


datafile=ROOT.TFile("file_name")
datatree=datafile.Get("tree_name")

leave_list=datatree.GetListOfLeaves()
opstr_list=[]
for leaf in leave_list:
        leaf_name=leaf.GetName()
        opstr=leaf_name+"=events."+leaf_name
        opstr_list.append(opstr)

for events in datatree:
        for op_str in opstr_list:
                exec(op_str)

        #then you can use your vars
```






*https://wiki.python.org/moin/pytest
*http://pythontesting.net/framework/pytest/pytest-introduction/

''The Merit''

A normal test file.

```
import unittest
from unnecessary_math import multiply
 
class TestUM(unittest.TestCase):
 
    def test_numbers_3_4(self):
        self.assertEqual( multiply(3,4), 12)
```

A simpler test file with the aid of `pytest`

```
from unnecessary_math import multiply
 
def test_numbers_3_4():
    assert( multiply(3,4) == 12 )
```

''How to run it?''

Two identical ways.

```
python -m pytest test_um_pytest.py
py.test test_um_pytest.py
```

with verbose

```
python -m pytest -v test_um_pytest.py
py.test -v test_um_pytest.py
```

''Using testing fixtures''

to setup and tear down before and after each test.

```
from unnecessary_math import multiply

def setup_module(module):
    print ("setup_module      module:%s" % module.__name__)

def teardown_module(module):
    print ("teardown_module   module:%s" % module.__name__)

def setup_function(function):
    print ("setup_function    function:%s" % function.__name__)

def teardown_function(function):
    print ("teardown_function function:%s" % function.__name__)

def test_numbers_3_4():
    print 'test_numbers_3_4  <============================ actual test code'
    assert multiply(3,4) == 12 

def test_strings_a_3():
    print 'test_strings_a_3  <============================ actual test code'
    assert multiply('a',3) == 'aaa' 


class TestUM:

    def setup(self):
        print ("setup             class:TestStuff")

    def teardown(self):
        print ("teardown          class:TestStuff")

    def setup_class(cls):
        print ("setup_class       class:%s" % cls.__name__)

    def teardown_class(cls):
        print ("teardown_class    class:%s" % cls.__name__)

    def setup_method(self, method):
        print ("setup_method      method:%s" % method.__name__)

    def teardown_method(self, method):
        print ("teardown_method   method:%s" % method.__name__)

    def test_numbers_5_6(self):
        print 'test_numbers_5_6  <============================ actual test code'
        assert multiply(5,6) == 30 

    def test_strings_b_2(self):
        print 'test_strings_b_2  <============================ actual test code'
        assert multiply('b',2) == 'bb'
```

A more complex version of argument control than [[Python getopt Package]].

*https://docs.python.org/2/library/argparse.html
*https://docs.python.org/2/howto/argparse.html

----

''The basics''

```
import argparse
parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
parser.parse_args()
```

use `python x.py --help`

''basic example''

```
import argparse
parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
parser.add_argument("echo")
args = parser.parse_args()
print args.echo
```

A more complex example

```
import argparse

parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description="calculate X to the power of Y")
group = parser.add_mutually_exclusive_group()
group.add_argument("-v", "--verbose", action="store_true")
group.add_argument("-q", "--quiet", action="store_true")
parser.add_argument("x", type=int, help="the base")
parser.add_argument("y", type=int, help="the exponent")
args = parser.parse_args()
answer = args.x**args.y

if args.quiet:
    print answer
elif args.verbose:
    print "{} to the power {} equals {}".format(args.x, args.y, answer)
else:
    print "{}^{} == {}".format(args.x, args.y, answer)
```






!!Composable command line interface toolkit

https://click.palletsprojects.com/en/7.x/

----

''example''

```
import click

@click.command()
@click.option("--count", default=1, help="Number of greetings.")
@click.option("--name", prompt="Your name",
              help="The person to greet.")
def hello(count, name):
    """Simple program that greets NAME for a total of COUNT times."""
    for _ in range(count):
        click.echo("Hello, %s!" % name)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    hello()
```

''usage''

```
$ python hello.py --count=3
```






The datetime module supplies classes for manipulating dates and times in both simple and complex ways. While date and time arithmetic is supported, the focus of the implementation is on efficient attribute extraction for output formatting and manipulation. For related functionality, see also the ''time'' and ''calendar'' modules.

https://docs.python.org/2/library/datetime.html

available objects: `date`,`datetime`,`time`,`timedelta`,`tzinfo`


```
import datetime
now = datetime.datetime.now()
print ("Current date and time : ")
print (now.strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"))
```

timedelta represents a duration of time. supports operation.

```
class datetime.timedelta([days[, seconds[, microseconds[, milliseconds[, minutes[, hours[, weeks]]]]]]])
```







*`'int' object has no attribute '__getitem__'` means that you're attempting to apply the index operator [] on an int, not a list.
